<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <title>Figma Combine Align and Scale Notes</title>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Lesson 29 — Figma: Combine, Align and Scale</h1>

<p>Basic shapes get you started, but most UI elements need shapes that don't
exist out of the box. Figma's boolean operations let you build them by
combining the ones you have.</p>

<h2>Boolean operations</h2>

<p>Select multiple shapes, then click the two-squares icon in the top center
toolbar. Four options drop down.</p>

<p>Union merges all selected shapes into one. Subtract removes the overlapping
area of one shape from another — useful for cutting holes. Intersect keeps only
the area where the shapes overlap and discards everything else. Exclude is the
opposite: it removes the overlapping area and keeps everything outside it.</p>

<h2>Aligning and distributing</h2>

<p>Select the objects you want to align and go to the design panel on the right.
The alignment tools sit at the top. The first six align elements relative to
each other: left edges, horizontal centers, right edges, top edges, vertical
centers, bottom edges. The last two distribute objects evenly across the
vertical or horizontal axis, so spacing between them becomes consistent without
manual adjustment.</p>

<h2>Scaling</h2>

<p>Dragging a corner resizes an object but doesn't scale everything inside it.
Effects, strokes and text sizes stay fixed even when the container grows or
shrinks. If you need everything to scale proportionally including those
properties, use the scale tool in the top-left corner of the screen instead.
Select the group or frame, click the scale tool, and drag. Everything inside,
including strokes, effects and text, scales with it.</p>

</body>
</html>